AB  - This research evaluates people’s language, especially the language used in mass protests. It reveals how protesters express their attitude towards Indonesian government’s institutions and policies as recorded in audio visual media between 2013 and 2015. The research displays thirteen different mass street orations. From the analysis, it can be seen that the research indicates that the protesters exploit all possible appraisal systems in their orations. They use three types of positive and negative attitudes: affect, judgement, and appreciation. In order to amplify their attitudes, they apply raised and sharpened graduation and single-voicing engagement systems. As a result, the protesters seem to challenge the government’s policies by producing critical, subjective, and abusive verbal attacks. For the sake of a check-and-balance control to the Indonesian government, the street orations will contribute to the formation of democratization in Indonesia, except the abusive language. © 2016 American Scientific Publishers All rights reserved.
