AB  - Purpose: This article investigates the level of health literacy on consumers' attitude and involvement toward Direct-to-Consumer pharmaceutical ads. Design/methodology/approach: This study adopted the newest vital sign (NVS) test as a measure for health literacy. Sixty-one college students first took the NVS test measuring their literacy level, then were exposed to a hypothetical print ad for prescription allergy medication and finally completed a questionnaire measuring their attitude, involvement and evaluation toward the ad. Findings: Participations in the higher health literacy were not involved with the ad and therefore not interested in the allergy medication. They showed negative attitude toward pharmaceutical ads. The higher the literacy, the more they agree with that pharmaceutical companies should not advertise to the general public. Results also indicate significant positive correlations between health literacy and evaluations of ads. The more literature the consumer, the more cognitively they processed the information from the ad. Research limitations/implications: The research was limited by the use of convenience sample. A more diverse sample across different age groups would provide a wider range of health literacy and more conclusive evidence. In addition, this study only examined print ads in a specific drug category. Other media and pharmaceutical products may provide different results. Practical implications: Our findings provide some guidance on pharmaceutical print ads. Results show that consumers with higher literacy are likely to process the ads cognitively and to be able to evaluate the ads. Given the nature of pharmaceutical products, companies need to understand health literacy levels of their intended target audience. Originality/value: Although health literacy has received attention among academicians and practitioners, its relationship with consumers' processing of pharmaceutical advertising is not clear. Our findings help provide some evidence of how health literacy affects consumers attitude and evaluation toward pharmaceutical advertising. © 2015, © W. S. Maney & Son Ltd 2015.
