AB  - Background/Aims: This study determined the attitude of physiotherapists from Trinidad and Tobago toward older adults and explored the relationships between these attitudes and selected demographic variables. This has become necessary as traditional reverence and respect for older adults is being eroded, and professionals’ attitudes are influenced by personal experiences and social biases. Methods: Forty physiotherapists were recruited and 30 (75%) participated. Data were collected using the Kogan’s Attitudes to Older People Scale (KOPS) and a data collection sheet. KOPS scores were divided into categories to reflect a range of attitude intensities from strongly negative to strongly positive. Descriptive and inferential statistics were used to analyse the data using SPSS software. The relationship between attitude and type of practice was analysed, but that between attitude and age, gender and academic qualification was not analysed owing to small subgroup numbers. Results: All participating physiotherapists treated older patients and reported that this exposure influenced their interactions with older patients. The mean KOPS score was 163.03 ±18.26 (median 162), reflecting a weak positive attitude. There was no statistically significant difference between the mean KOPS scores of private and public practitioners (t(28) -1.51, p = 0.14), but private practitioners had a marginally higher mean score. Conclusions: Physiotherapists in Trinidad and Tobago showed a weak positive attitude to older adults. © 2015 MA Healthcare Ltd.
