AB  - Although experiences with external heterosexism are common (including sexual minority-related harassment, victimization, and discrimination), little is known about what may buffer the association between external heterosexism and internalizing negative attitudes about minority sexual orientation (internalized heterosexism). Building on Meyer’s (2003) minority stress model, we examined the moderating effects of social constraints in talking about sexual orientation with both lesbian, gay, and bisexual (LGB) friends and heterosexual friends as well as collective self-esteem on the association between self-reported lifetime external heterosexism and internalized heterosexism. Self-identified sexual minority women (N 140), recruited through LGBT organizations and social media, completed an online survey. Results of regression analyses revealed that both fewer social constraints with LGB friends and greater collective self-esteem buffered the negative effects of external heterosexism on internalized heterosexism. There was also an interaction of external heterosexism by social constraints with heterosexual friends on internalized heterosexism, but it did not reflect a buffering effect. Under low social constraints, more frequent experience with external heterosexism was associated with more internalized heterosexism. Under high social constraints, there was no effect of external heterosexism on internalized heterosexism. Taken together, the results highlight the importance of LGB social and group-related processes as positive assets in buffering the impact of external heterosexism on internalized heterosexism. © 2015 American Psychological Association.
